## OVERVIEW:
This project is a Turing Machine implementation in java. It reads a formatted input txt file to instantiate a turing machine complete with a tape and transition table. The input file can include a starting tape, otherwise the starting tape contains a blank.

The turing machine can move left or right on the tape and uses the transition table to read from the tape and move between states. All states have a valid transition for every character in the alphabet of the tape.

## INCLUDED FILES:
    * TMSimulator.java -- main class, reads an input file and simulates the read TM
    * TMTape.java -- tape class, used to instantiate tapes to read and write from
    * TMTransition.java -- transition class, used to instantiate transitions for the TM

## COMPILING AND RUNNING:
From the directory containing all source files, compile the
driver class (and all dependencies) with the command:
* $ javac tm/TMSimulator.java

Run the compiled class file with the command:
* $ java tm.TMSimulator [filename]
where filename is the path to a .txt file formatted to be read by TMSimulator.java

The program will output the state of the TM's tape at the time of halting.

Formatted .txt file should follow the format:
Line 1: The number of states
Line 2: The size of the alphabet (excluding blank)
Line 3 to n: Transitions using the format (toState, write, move L/R)
    ex: 1, 1, R - Goes to state 1, writes 1 to the tape, and moves the tape head right.
Line n (final line): The starting tape, leave blank to make the starting tape blank.

## PROGRAM DESIGN AND IMPORTANT CONCEPTS:
The TMSimulator class is responsible for creating and running a TM. It contains an instance of TMTape and TMTransition, as well as keeping its own HashTable to store transitions. It's runtime is broken into three main parts:
    1. Validate and load the input file
    2. Setup the TM by reading the file
    3. Step through the Turing Machine until it halts
The turing machine knows how many states it has, the size of its alphabet, all of its transitions, and the contents of the tape. This class also tracks the current state. The class is set up to get more complicated setup done in step 2 so that step 3 can be a simple loop, since that is where most of runtime will be spent.

The TMTape class is the main class responsible for making this a Turing Machine. The tape is an arraylist which can be read from and written to left or right. It populates missing values with blanks.

The TMTransition class holds a transition object, which keeps track of its toState, write, and if it moves the tape left or right. It was written to work with the HashTable in TMSimulator, which uses the fromState and onCharacter as a key to obtain the correct transition. This setup was chosen because of the format of the input files, where the fromState and onCharacter are implied.

## TESTING:
The main source of testing was using the provided test files (file0,2,5.txt), and comparing our output to the expected output in the project specifications. We also printed out additional info in TMSimulator's output to make sure things like the tape head and output length were matching the expectations, which we later removed so our output would match the grader.

I also wrote an additional test file which I tweaked to try out edge cases, such as a single state TM. This helped me catch a few bugs which weren't apparent using the three provided files.

## DISCUSSION:
Initially, I made TMState a class rather than TMTransition, but I realized that the states themselves don't need to contain information here, it seemed more intuitive to just save the state number as a variable since we know the state names are integers and the final state is the highest number. I pivoted to having TMTransition be a class instead. I chose to use an ArrayList for reading the tape, and a HashTable for the transition table. I chose an ArrayList for the tape because it has a get() of O(1), and its worst case is adding to the start of the array, which doesn't happen much in the test files. A goal of mine was to keep the overall structure of this project simple to maximize runtime, so I relied a lot on the known confines of this program's TMs.  If I had more time, I would try to find a more efficient datastructure than ArrayList for the purpose of the tape. --Dean

